# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: frank-dawson-adams
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolphe-basile-routhier] Routhier was born and grew up in Saint-Placide, Quebec, on his family's farm.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolphe-basile-routhier] He attended Séminaire de Ste-Thérèse, and later studied law at Université Laval.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolphe-basile-routhier] He graduated and was called to the Quebec bar in 1861.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolphe-basile-routhier] Routhier practised law in Kamouraska until he was appointed to the Quebec Superior Court in 1873 (as Chief Justice from 1904 to 1906) and local judge in admiralty of the Exchequer Court of Canada (from 1897 to 1906).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolphe-basile-routhier] Routhier ran as a Conservative candidate for the riding of Kamouraska in several federal elections, but he was never elected.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolphe-basile-routhier] Routhier wrote a number of books under the name Jean Piquefort.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolphe-basile-routhier] Routhier's poem "Ô Canada" was commissioned by the Lieutenant Governor of Quebec Théodore Robitaille for the 1880 Saint-Jean-Baptiste Day ceremony.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolphe-basile-routhier] In June 1914, Routhier was one of the three judges appointed to conduct the Commission of Inquiry into the sinking of the Canadian Pacific steamship *Empress of Ireland*, which had resulted in the loss of 1,012 lives.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolphe-basile-routhier] Routhier married Clorinde Mondelet on November 12, 1862, in Quebec and had one son.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/adolphe-basile-routhier] Many sites and landmarks were named to honour Basile Routhier.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] In freshwater, particularly those on non-limestone terrains, alkalinities are low and involve a lot of ions.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] In the ocean, on the other hand, alkalinity is completely dominated by carbonate and bicarbonate plus a small contribution from borate.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Although alkalinity is primarily a term used by limnologists and oceanographers, it is also used by hydrologists to describe temporary hardness.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Moreover, measuring alkalinity is important in determining a stream's ability to neutralize acidic pollution from rainfall or wastewater.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] It is one of the best measures of the sensitivity of the stream to acid inputs.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] There can be long-term changes in the alkalinity of streams and rivers in response to human disturbances such as acid rain generated by SO*x* and NO*x* emissions.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] In 1884, Professor Wilhelm (William) Dittmar of Anderson College, now the University of Strathclyde, analysed 77 pristine seawater samples from around the world brought back by the Challenger expedition.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] He found that in seawater the major ions were in a fixed ratio, confirming the hypothesis of Johan Georg Forchhammer, that is now known as the Principle of Constant Proportions.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Dittmar found that the concentration of calcium was slightly greater in the deep ocean, and named this increase alkalinity.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Also in 1884, Svante Arrhenius submitted his PhD theses in which he advocated the existence of ions in solution, and defined acids as hydronium ion donors and bases as hydroxide ion donors.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] For that work, he received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1903.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] See also Svante Arrhenius#Ionic disassociation.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Alkalinity roughly refers to the molar equivalent concentration of bases in a solution that can be converted to uncharged species by a strong acid.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Molar equivalent concentration means the charge-equivalent concentration of single-charge ions.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] For example, 1 mole of HCO− 3 in solution represents 1 molar equivalent, while 1 mole of CO2− 3 is 2 molar equivalents because twice as many H+ ions would be necessary to balance the charge.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] The total charge of a solution always equals zero.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] This leads to a parallel definition of alkalinity that is based upon the charge balance of ions in a solution.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Certain ions, including Na+, K+, Ca2+, Mg2+, Cl−, SO2− 4, and NO− 3 are "*conservative*" such that they are not affected by changes in temperature, pressure or pH, in contrast to nonconservative ions such as HCO− 3 that are.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Isolating the conservative ions on one side of this charge balance equation, makes the nonconservative ions which accept or donate protons and thus define alkalinity clustered on the other side of the equation.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] This combined charge balance and proton balance is called **total alkalinity**.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Total alkalinity is not (much) affected by temperature, pressure, or pH, and is thus itself a conservative measurement, which increases its usefulness in aquatic systems.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] All anions except HCO− 3 and CO2− 3 have low concentrations in Earth's surface water (streams, rivers, and lakes).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Thus **carbonate alkalinity**, which is equal to [HCO− 3] + 2[CO2− 3] is also approximately equal to the total alkalinity in surface water.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Alkalinity measures the ability of a solution to neutralize acids to the equivalence point of carbonate or bicarbonate, defined as pH 4.5 for many oceanographic/limnological studies.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] The alkalinity is equal to the stoichiometric sum of the bases in solution.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] In most Earth surface waters carbonate alkalinity tends to make up most of the total alkalinity because of dissolution of commonly occurring carbonate rocks along with other geological weathering processes that produce carbonate anions.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Other common natural components that can contribute to alkalinity include borate, hydroxide, phosphate, silicate, dissolved ammonia, and the conjugate bases of organic acids (e.g., acetate).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Solutions produced in a laboratory may contain a virtually limitless number of species that contribute to alkalinity.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Alkalinity is frequently given as molar equivalents per liter of solution or per kilogram of solvent.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] In commercial (e.g. the swimming pool industry) and regulatory contexts, alkalinity might also be given in parts per million of equivalent calcium carbonate (ppm CaCO3).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Alkalinity is sometimes incorrectly used interchangeably with basicity, but they are different measurements.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] For example, the addition of CO2 lowers the pH of a solution, thus reducing basicity while alkalinity remains unchanged (see example below).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] A variety of titrants, endpoints, and indicators are specified for various alkalinity measurement methods.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Hydrochloric and sulfuric acids are common acid titrants, while phenolpthalein, methyl red, and bromocresol green are common indicators.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] (Subscript T indicates the total concentration of the species in the solution as measured.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Alkalinity can be measured by titrating a sample with a strong acid until all the buffering capacity of the aforementioned ions above the pH of bicarbonate or carbonate is consumed.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] This point is functionally set to pH 4.5.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] At this point, all the bases of interest have been protonated to the zero level species, hence they no longer cause alkalinity.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] In the carbonate system the bicarbonate ions [HCO− 3] and the carbonate ions [CO2− 3] have become converted to carbonic acid [H2CO3] at this pH.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] This pH is also called the CO2 equivalence point where the major component in water is dissolved CO2 which is converted to H2CO3 in an aqueous solution.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] There are no strong acids or bases at this point.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Therefore, the alkalinity is modeled and quantified with respect to the CO2 equivalence point.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Because the alkalinity is measured with respect to the CO2 equivalence point, the dissolution of CO2, although it adds acid and dissolved inorganic carbon, does not change the alkalinity.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] In natural conditions, the dissolution of basic rocks and addition of ammonia [NH3] or organic amines leads to the addition of base to natural waters at the CO2 equivalence point.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] The dissolved base in water increases the pH and titrates an equivalent amount of CO2 to bicarbonate ion and carbonate ion.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] At equilibrium, the water contains a certain amount of alkalinity contributed by the concentration of weak acid anions.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Conversely, the addition of acid converts weak acid anions to CO2 and continuous addition of strong acids can cause the alkalinity to become less than zero.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] It can be seen from the above protonation reactions that most bases consume one proton (H+) to become a neutral species, thus increasing alkalinity by one per equivalent.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] CO2− 3 however, will consume two protons before becoming a zero-level species (CO2), thus it increases alkalinity by two per mole of CO2− 3. [H+] and [HSO− 4] decrease alkalinity, as they act as sources of protons.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] They are often represented collectively as [H+]T.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Alkalinity is typically reported as mg/L *as* CaCO3.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] (The conjunction "as" is appropriate in this case because the alkalinity results from a mixture of ions but is reported "as if" all of this is due to CaCO3.) This can be converted into milliequivalents per Liter (meq/L) by dividing by 50 (the approximate MW of CaCO3 divided by 2).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Addition (or removal) of CO2 to a solution does not change its alkalinity, since the net reaction produces the same number of equivalents of positively contributing species (H+) as negative contributing species (HCO− 3 and/or CO2− 3).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Adding CO2 to the solution lowers its pH, but does not affect alkalinity.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Addition of CO2 to a solution in contact with a solid can (over time) affect the alkalinity, especially for carbonate minerals in contact with groundwater or seawater.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] The dissolution (or precipitation) of carbonate rock has a strong influence on the alkalinity.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] This is because carbonate rock is composed of CaCO3 and its dissociation will add Ca2+ and CO2− 3 into solution.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Ca2+ will not influence alkalinity, but CO2− 3 will increase alkalinity by 2 units.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Increased dissolution of carbonate rock by acidification from acid rain and mining has contributed to increased alkalinity concentrations in some major rivers throughout the eastern U.S.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] The lower the pH, the higher the concentration of bicarbonate will be.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] This shows how a lower pH can lead to higher alkalinity if the amount of bicarbonate produced is greater than the amount of H+ remaining after the reaction.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] This is the case since the amount of acid in the rainwater is low.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] If this alkaline groundwater later comes into contact with the atmosphere, it can lose CO2, precipitate carbonate, and thereby become less alkaline again.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] shows that pH will be related to calcium ion concentration, with lower pH going with higher calcium ion concentration.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] In this case, the higher the pH, the more bicarbonate and carbonate ion there will be, in contrast to the paradoxical situation described above, where one does not have equilibrium with the atmosphere.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] In the ocean, alkalinity is completely dominated by carbonate and bicarbonate plus a small contribution from borate.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] There are many methods of alkalinity generation in the ocean.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Perhaps the most well known is the dissolution of calcium carbonate to form Ca2+ and CO2− 3 (carbonate).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] The carbonate ion has the potential to absorb two hydrogen ions.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Therefore, it causes a net increase in ocean alkalinity.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Calcium carbonate dissolution occurs in regions of the ocean which are undersaturated with respect to calcium carbonate.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] The increasing carbon dioxide level in the atmosphere, due to carbon dioxide emissions, results in increasing absorption of CO2 from the atmosphere into the oceans.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] This does not affect the ocean's alkalinity but it does result in a reduction in pH value (called ocean acidification).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Ocean alkalinity enhancement has been proposed as one option to add alkalinity to the ocean and therefore buffer against pH changes.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Biological processes have a much greater impact on oceanic alkalinity on short (minutes to centuries) timescales.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Denitrification and sulfate reduction occur in oxygen-limited environments.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Both of these processes consume hydrogen ions (thus increasing alkalinity) and release gases (N2 or H2S), which eventually escape into the atmosphere.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Nitrification and sulfide oxidation both decrease alkalinity by releasing protons as a byproduct of oxidation reactions.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] The ocean's alkalinity varies over time, most significantly over geologic timescales (millennia).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Changes in the balance between terrestrial weathering and sedimentation of carbonate minerals (for example, as a function of ocean acidification) are the primary long-term drivers of alkalinity in the ocean.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Over human timescales, mean ocean alkalinity is relatively stable.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Seasonal and annual variability of mean ocean alkalinity is very low.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Alkalinity varies by location depending on evaporation/precipitation, advection of water, biological processes, and geochemical processes.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] River dominated mixing also occurs close to the shore; it is strongest close to the mouth of a large river.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Here, the rivers can act as either a source or a sink of alkalinity.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] AT follows the outflow of the river and has a linear relationship with salinity.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Oceanic alkalinity also follows general trends based on latitude and depth.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] It has been shown that AT is often inversely proportional to sea surface temperature (SST).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Therefore, it generally increases with high latitudes and depths.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] As a result, upwelling areas (where water from the deep ocean is pushed to the surface) also have higher alkalinity values.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] There are many programs to measure, record, and study oceanic alkalinity, together with many of the other characteristics of seawater, like temperature and salinity.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] These include: GEOSECS (Geochemical Ocean Sections Study), TTO/NAS (Transient Tracers in the Ocean/North Atlantic Study), JGOFS (Joint Global Ocean Flux Study), WOCE (World Ocean Circulation Experiment), CARINA (Carbon dioxide in the Atlantic Ocean).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Some carbon removal techniques add alkalinity to the ocean and therefore immediately buffer pH changes which might help the organisms in the region that the extra alkalinity is added to.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] The two technologies that fall into this category are ocean alkalinity enhancement and electrochemical methods.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Eventually, due to diffusion, that alkalinity addition will be quite small to distant waters.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] This is why the term *local ocean acidification mitigation* is used.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] Both of these technologies have the potential to operate on a large scale and to be efficient at removing carbon dioxide.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/alkalinity] However, they are expensive, have many risks and side effects, and currently have a low technology readiness level.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The **American Academy of Arts and Sciences** (**The Academy**) is one of the oldest learned societies in the United States.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It was founded in 1780 during the American Revolution by John Adams, John Hancock, James Bowdoin, Andrew Oliver, and other Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Membership in the academy is achieved through a nominating petition, review, and election process.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy's quarterly journal, *Dædalus*, is published by the MIT Press on behalf of the academy, and has been open-access since January 2021.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy also conducts multidisciplinary public policy research.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Patton has served as President of the Academy since January 2025.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The first class of new members, chosen by the Academy in 1781, included Benjamin Franklin and George Washington as well as several international honorary members.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The initial volume of Academy *Memoirs* appeared in 1785, and the *Proceedings* followed in 1846.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the 1950s, the Academy launched its journal *Daedalus*, reflecting its commitment to a broader intellectual and socially-oriented program.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Since the second half of the twentieth century, independent research has become a central focus of the Academy.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1950s, arms control emerged as one of its signature concerns.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy also served as the catalyst in establishing the National Humanities Center in North Carolina.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1990s, the Academy developed a new strategic plan, focusing on four major areas: science, technology, and global security; social policy and education; humanities and culture; and education.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In 2002, the Academy established a visiting scholars program in association with Harvard University.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] More than 75 academic institutions from across the country have become Affiliates of the Academy to support this program and other Academy initiatives.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy has sponsored a number of awards and prizes, throughout its history and has offered opportunities for fellowships and visiting scholars at the Academy.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In July 2013, *The Boston Globe* exposed then president Leslie Berlowitz for falsifying her credentials, faking a doctorate, and consistently mistreating her staff.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is modeled on the Science and Engineering Indicators, published biennially by the National Science Board as required by Congress.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Ever since the founding of the Academy, its members have been nominated and elected by peers.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Members of the Academy included not only scientists and scholars, but also writers and artists as well as representatives from the full range of professions and public life.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Throughout the Academy's history, more than 10,000 fellows have been elected.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Astronomer Maria Mitchell was the first woman elected to the Academy, in 1848.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The current membership encompasses over 5,700 members based across the United States and around the world.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Academy members include more than 250 Nobel laureates and more than 60 Pulitzer Prize winners.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Of the Academy's 14,343 members since 1780, 1,406 are or have been affiliated with Harvard University, 611 with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 433 with Yale University, 425 with the University of California, Berkeley, and 404 with Stanford University.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The following table includes those institutions affiliated with 300 or more members.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] † Excludes members affiliated exclusively with associated national laboratories.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] As of 2023, membership is divided into five classes and thirty specialties.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] Frank Dawson Adams was born into a prosperous, middle-class family in Montreal, Canada East.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] Adams attended the High School of Montreal (a private school founded in 1843 and closely associated with McGill University after 1852).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] As a pupil there, Adams received a classical education, and his knowledge of Latin was valuable later in life in his historical studies.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] At the age of sixteen he entered the Applied Science Program at McGill University, where he studied geology with John William Dawson (Principal of McGill since 1852) and Bernard Harrington (who had set up the Applied Science program).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] He graduated with first class honors in Applied Science in 1878, then spent a year at the Yale Scientific School, where he studied German, French, and mineralogy.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] It was there that he met George Wessel Hawes (1848-1882) a pioneer American petrologist, who had worked with Harry Rosenbusch in Germany.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] He also met a fellow-student, Andrew Cowper Lawson, and in 1888 they published a joint paper on their investigation of the mineral scapolite.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] Returning to Montreal, he was appointed Assistant Chemist at the Geological Survey of Canada (GSC), and the following year (when the GSC moved to Ottawa), Assistant Chemist and Petrographer.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] He received a leave of absence to spend at least part of two years in Heidelberg, studying with Harry Rosenbusch, who by that time was the acknowledged master of microscopic petrography of igneous rocks.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] Rosenbusch attracted students from many different countries.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] While Adams was in Heidelberg he met G.H.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] Diller, both of whom later became leading American petrologists, as well as Victor Goldschmidt and (Carl) Alfred Osann (1859–1923), who became famous geochemists in Europe.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] In 1883, Adams published the first work in Canada that made full use of the petrographic microscope, as well as a paper indicating that he had already begun the field work north of Montreal, that later became the basis of his doctorate at Heidelberg.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] He received a master's degree from McGill in 1884, and his Ph.D. from Heidelberg University in 1892.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] His doctoral studies on the Morin anorthosite showed that these rocks were not metamorphosed sediments, as thought previously, but were igneous rocks that had been intruded into Grenville sediments and later metamorphosed in the Grenville orogeny.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] In 1889 Adams was appointed Lecturer in Geology at McGill University.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] He was appointed Logan Professor of Geology after the retirement of John William Dawson in 1892 and held this position until his own retirement in 1924.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] Though he was working full-time at McGill, he continued to spend summers in the field, financed by the GSC.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] In 1891 he began working on the Grenville of eastern Ontario, and by the following year had started to work on the Haliburton, Ontario area.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] His work there, carried out after 1896 with Alfred Barlow of the GSC, was published as a GSC Memoir in 1908, and became a classic of Canadian geology.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] The rocks, which included unusual alkaline rocks, were not merely mapped, but studied in detail using petrographic and chemical methods, and firm conclusions were drawn about their petrogenesis, all of which was unusual for a GSC Memoir at that time.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] This was well before comparable work was carried out in Germany or the United States.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] Adams remained at McGill, where he served as the Dean of the Faculty of Applied Science and then as Vice-Principal to the University.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] He served as President of the International Geological Congress held in Toronto in 1913, and was President of the Geological Society of America in 1917.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] The Frank Dawson Adams Building at McGill University is named in his honor.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] A plaque in his honor was erected on the Redpath Museum on the McGill campus in 1950.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] He retired from McGill in 1924, and began to travel widely, collecting books on the history of geology, as well as rocks and minerals for McGill.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] He published several papers on the geology of Ceylon and also on the history of geology, culminating in his book *Birth and Development of the Geological Sciences* (1938).
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] It became a classic and was reprinted by Dover Publications in 1954.
[src:frank-dawson-adams/frank-dawson-adams] He left his rare book collection (1581 monographs) to McGill university.
